contributors—all leading social scientists in their fields—suggest that these global transformations will require youth to develop new skills, sensibilities, and habits of mind that are far ahead of what most educational systems can now deliver. Drawing from comparative and interdisciplinary materials, the authors examine the complex psychological, sociocultural, and historical implications of globalization for children and youth growing up today. The book explores why new and broader global visions are needed to educate children and youth to be informed, engaged, and critical citizens in the new millennium. Published in association with the Ross Institute  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCulture. 0aEducation. 0aGlobalization. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh  achildren.  acoming of age.  acultural context.  acultural history.  acultural studies.  ademographics.  aeconomics.  aeconomy.  aeducation.  aglobal citizens.  aglobal.  aglobalization.  agrassroots.  agrowing up.  ahistorical context.  ahistorical.  ainterdisciplinary.  ainternational.  amodern world.  apolicy change.  apolicy.  apsychology.  asocial history.  asocial science.  asocial scientists.  asocial studies.  asociocultural.  atechnology.  aterra incognita.  atransformation.1 aBattro, Antonio M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBloom, David E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoatsworth, John H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGardner, Howard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJenkins, Henry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaira, Sunaina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aQin-Hill